depends on local leaders and staff who are committed to quality and ensuring that appropriate care is provided the first time around</p> </blockquote> <p>And Steve Kell, NHSCC Leadership Co-Chair and chair of Bassetlaw CCG, adds:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It is welcome that there is an increasing emphasis on Boards owning complaints within their organisations. However for the system to be fully assured that issues are being identified and addresses, this information will need to be aligned with the soft and hard data being collected and analysed by CCGs.<br />We fully recognise that as CCGs and others continue to shine a light on quality within the NHS more problems are likely to emerge. Regulator will need to work with local commissioners to identify where improvement is needed and coordinate actions to resolving issues as they emerge.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T14:59:10.032Z\">at 2.59pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528b73b6e4b0f15d741f6140\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T14:31:36.694Z\">2.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Helen Crane writes</em></p> <p>Nice, who the government's response to the Francis report states will take the lead on producing guidance on NHS staffing levels, have provided some further details on what this will involve<a href=\"http://www.nice.org.uk/newsroom/news/NICEToProduceGuidanceSafeNHSStaffingLevels.jsp\"> on their website</a>.</p> <p>They say they will undertake a &quot;comprehensive review of the evidence relating staffing levels, and will produce definitive guidance on safe and efficient staffing levels in a range of NHS settings&quot;. The guidance will initially focus on adult wards in acute in-patient settings, befofe guidance on safer staffing levels in other areas is published from August 2014 onwards.</p> <p>Nice chief executive, professor Gillian Leng, says:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Nice is going to play a key role in ensuring that NHS services have enough staff to provide efficient, safe care for patients. At first, we will focus on nurses in hospital wards where patients need urgent short-term care.</p> <p>&quot;There is already a lot of information available to help us develop the guidance which will allow NHS organisations and organisations providing care to NHS patients set safe and efficient staffing levels.</p> <p>&quot;The work will help to ensure that no matter where people live, they should be able to have access to appropriately staffed services.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T14:33:08.455Z\">at 2.33pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528b6f52e4b02747f7fb8f01\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T14:11:40.051Z\">2.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Claire Burke writes</em></p> <p>Hospitals that are not honest about medical blunders <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/nov/19/hospitals-mistakes-jeremy-hunt\">could have to pay some of the damages that follow and even lose their insurance cover</a>, under government plans to improve NHS patient safety.&nbsp;Jeremy Hunt says the plan would give hospitals an incentive to be open about blunders. Guardian health correspondent Denis Campbell writes:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Under his plan, hospitals that mislead or conceal information from patients affected by mistakes or from grieving relatives could either lose their indemnity cover or have it reduced. They may also be punished by having to pay out of their own funds part of the cost of settling lawsuits brought by patients, which can cost up to &pound;10m in compensation and legal fees, to force them to be much more open when medical negligence occurs. Hunt said that if a hospital was not open with patients and their families following a patient safety incident, its indemnity cover – which is key to its functioning – could be reduced or removed. That would give hospitals &quot;a strong financial incentive to be open about patient safety incidents&quot;, he said.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b6b08e4b05b42ae1b6a1b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T13:53:18.117Z\">1.53pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Helen Crane writes</em></p> <p>Here are the first reactions to the government's response to the Francis report on Twitter:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/GabrielScally/statuses/402784251583553536\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Hunt ignores Francis on statutory personal duty of candor. That's a pity. Francis was right on that. GMC already has code that covers it.</p>— Gabriel Scally (@GabrielScally) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GabrielScally/statuses/402784251583553536\">November 19, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BenNunnUK/statuses/402793518311022592\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>From <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DHgovuk\">@DHgovuk</a>'s response to <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Francis&amp;src=hash\">#Francis</a> &quot;friends and family test will be extended to mental health settings&quot; by end of Dec 2014 <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MindCharity\">@MindCharity</a></p>— Ben Nunn (@BenNunnUK) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BenNunnUK/statuses/402793518311022592\">November 19, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/KailashChandOBE/statuses/402793956104491008\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Govt response to <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23francis&amp