ass=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T11:22:52.177Z\">11.22am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Clare Horton writes</em></p> <p>Writing for Comment is free, Simon Wessely, head of the department of psychological medicine, Institute of Psychiatry, at King's College London, looks at Jeremy Hunt's pledge to let patients <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2508105/Pick-GP-like-Families-register-near-work-school-surgery-hours-suit-them.html\">pick a GP wherever they like. </a>It is hard to think of a single policy that will do more to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/19/any-gp-so-long-as-you-are-healthy\">extend the health gap between rich and poor</a> than Hunt's latest plans, says Wessely. He explains:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>GP practices are going to be rated on a scale of one to four. Guess who won't be seen by the top-scoring practices: those who can't travel very far, because of a medical condition or because they don't have transport; those ill-informed about how to play the system; those mentally troubled, or with learning difficulties or dementia. Guess who will be seen: the affluent, information-rich and mobile.</p> <p>And there will be other casualties. At the moment GPs know a lot about families, especially problem ones. That's why the GP is so vital to child protection. But what if you don't want anyone to know much about your family – to make a link between the troubled behaviour of a child, the bruise on the mum's arm and the smell of alcohol on the father's breath? Simple, register them all with different GPs separated by reasonable distance. And if you think the NHS's IT services will solve this problem, then you don't know much about NHS IT.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b3fdde4b05b42ae1b6a0a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T10:50:19.414Z\">10.50am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Claire Burke writes</em></p> <p>George Eaton says <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/11/nhs-crisis-none-parties-will-discuss-how-pay-it\">no party is willing to talk about how to pay for the NHS</a>. In an opinion piece for the New Statesman he writes about the proposals put forward by the think-tank Reform today (mentioned in the morning headlines), which call for a &pound;10 charge for GP consultations, &pound;10 fines for missed appointments, the introduction of a means-tested system for end of life care and an increase in prescription charges from &pound;7.85 to &pound;10:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Perhaps unsurprisingly, the Department of Health has responded by dismissing the idea out of hand. A spokesman said: &quot;We have been absolutely clear that the NHS should be free at the point of use, with access based on need. That is why we have increased health spending in real terms alongside &pound;20bn of efficiency savings to make sure the NHS continues to provide excellent care.&quot; Labour, meanwhile,&nbsp;spying an opportunity to cause&nbsp;political mischief, has commented: &quot;Patients will be alarmed that friends of Number 10 want to see charges for GP appointments and hospital care. &quot;</p> </blockquote> <p>Eaton concludes:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>But this merely defers the question of how we will ultimately pay for a health service of the standard the public both expect and deserve. Will any party grasp this nettle before 2015? Don't count on it.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b3d10e4b02747f7fb8ecc\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T10:50:04.334Z\">10.50am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Clare Horton writes</em></p> <p>Chris Ham, chief executive of the King's Fund thinktank, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/profchrisham/status/402681631590187008\">has tweeted</a>:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/profchrisham/statuses/402681631590187008\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>on day govt responds to Francis, politicians of all parties should aim 'to do no harm': change depends on local leaders and staff <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23kflead&amp;src=hash\">#kflead</a></p>— Chris Ham (@profchrisham) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/profchrisham/statuses/402681631590187008\">November 19, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b3671e4b010b65d556150\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T10:27:09.303Z\">10.27am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Clare Horton writes</em></p> <p>England's chief nursing officer, Jane Cummings, has told the BBC that <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-24997531\">publishing staffing numbers on individual wards will help give patients confidence</a> in the care they receive (see <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2013/nov/19/today-in-healthcare-tuesday-19-november#block-528b1f10e4b02747f7fb8eae\">morning headlines</a>). She said staff also needed to be given support to provide good care.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-ed6fa9d8-2552-4ad9-9a79-eaedc3e5a8fc\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/11/19/1384853184202/418f8211-7e0d-423a-be01-f612b1e52294-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Jane Cummings.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Jane Cummings. Photograph: Christoper Thomond</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b32f8e4b05b42ae1b69ff\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T09:59:06.189Z\">9.59am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Clare Horton writes</em></p> <p>On his NHS Managers blog, healthcare commentator Roy Lilley <a href=\"http://campaign.r20.constantcontact.com/render?llr=zfxea5cab&amp;v=001OwqOR7yhbtVt7Mu5Kakz0CjAtIrVV0B4X-Y4H0UsV-FYMg-e8N-inRBts86lsnEL_sXGaR8mqyBqNjDIE6YgNM1hQbhLrDQ2QcAAw8IVDO4ifqT5joXDsiz8_cWzX_MYpz35OUrlqESveZzZQiaHmifw23EGW4_2TSLl2ZLU7xsPBhTalZy8Hw%3D%3D\">looks ahead to Jeremy Hunt's Commons statement</a> on the government's final response to the Francis report. He writes:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Do we need to ask how situations develop where colleagues think it is better to construct lies about patients not getting treated than to actually build services where patients do get treated?</p> <p>We know, don't we? We know that the fear of criticism and the fear of explaining to a line-manager can be greater than the fear of having to explain to a patient. Board; more scared of the regulators than the relatives. They all end up doing asymmetric, mental calculations; the loss of face and the prospect of more pressure appear much larger than anything to be gained from the truth.</p> </blockquote> <p>He points the finger at regulators and says &quot;the very organisations, set up to keep us safe have made the NHS a more dangerous place&quot;. And he adds:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>This whole paradigm needs rethinking. Just how do we get the best from the NHS all the time, every time? The answer is in the question. Look for the best. Find, promote and celebrate the best. A new organisation; the NAfFS. The National Agency for Fabulous Stuff.</p> <p>Yes, I know, a Naff idea but, think for a moment. When Colchester fell behind with their cancer treatments, they had two options. Confess or lie. How about giving them a third option. </p> <p>Just suppose they could have called the NAfFS and said; we have a problem treating cancer patients. Tell us; who is doing it well and will you ask them to help us, please? Just suppose the Trust with the solution was paid a consultancy fee for helping. Wouldn't that simple investment be cheaper than special measures, less costly than the damage to the NHS's reputation we have now and a sensible start to doing things safer and better?</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b2e52e4b010b65d55614c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T09:31:28.813Z\">9.31am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Helen Crane writes</em></p> <p>New on the network, we have an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2013/nov/19/bob-ricketts-nhs-england-commissioning\">interview with Bob Ricketts of NHS England</a>, in which he explains how the organisation will make services more efficient. He believes that commissioning support is vital to ensuring that clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) get the best for their patients and taxpayers.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>What we are looking to do is create an efficient and effective market in commissioning support, to wrap around and support commissioners. But commissioners, whether they are CCGs or NHS England, will remain responsible and accountable for commissioning</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528b1f10e4b02747f7fb8eae\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-19T08:55:13.750Z\">8.55am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Morning headlines</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Helen Crane writes</em></p> <p>Good morning and welcome to the daily live blog from the Guardian Healthcare Professionals Network. Throughout the day, we'll be bringing you news, comment and analysis from around the web.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/nov/19/jeremy-hunt-hospitals-ward-staffing-levels\">The Guardian reports </a>that health secretary Jeremy Hunt will later announce that NHS trusts will be required to publish ward staffing figures every month from next April. However, he will reject a fixed nurse-patient ratio. This is in response to the Francis report, which exposed failures of care in the Mid Staffordshire NHS trust. The health secretary will make his speech to parliament at 1pm. </p> <p>Right-wing think tank Reform has suggested that prescription charges should be raised to &pound;10, <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-24985242\">says the BBC</a>. Its report, published today, suggests that increasing the charge from &pound;7.85 could fund NHS services. Under its proposals there would be exemptions for people on low incomes, but not necessarily all pensioners. </p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-0fbe892e-fafb-4ce1-8a1c-61d3e8161677\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/11/19/1384851223153/417ac1ee-0b03-4748-aa34-affe485b01b3-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Reform think tank have suggested that the price of a prescription could be raised to &pound;10.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Reform think tank have suggested that the price of a prescription could be raised to &pound;10. Photograph: Patty Chen/Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p>A <a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/getting-vaccinated-is-a-civic-dutywarn-health-experts-8947842.html\">new report has advised</a> that UK citizens should be given vaccination record cards and told that it is their &quot;civic duty&quot; to get immunised, according to the Independent.</p> <p>And <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/10458175/Contraceptive-pill-doubles-glaucoma-risk.html\">the Telegraph reports</a> on new evidence which suggests that women who take the contraceptive pill for more than three years are twice as likely to suffer from glaucoma and should be routinely screened.</p> <p>If there's a story, report or event you'd like to highlight – or you would like to share your thoughts on any of the healthcare issues in the news today – you can get in touch by leaving a comment below the line or tweeting us at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://twitter.com/GdnHealthcare\">@GdnHealthcare</a>.</p> </div> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422822293|2013-11-21T11:27:41Z|90c6cf8f78f0c3865c8c8891baf52c236f727b31 -->",
